    explanation: "This patient presents with a first episode of psychosis characterised by persecutory delusions, third-person auditory hallucinations (commentary type), significant functional decline over 8 months, and negative symptoms (flat affect, social withdrawal). A formal diagnosis of schizophrenia requires 6 months of continuous disturbance — while the overall timeline exceeds this, the full psychotic symptoms have been present for 3 months, making 'first episode psychosis' the clinically appropriate working diagnosis at this stage. Australian clinical guidelines strongly advocate for Early Psychosis Intervention (EPI) programs, which provide intensive, coordinated care including low-dose antipsychotic therapy, CBT for psychosis, family support, and vocational assistance, demonstrably improving long-term outcomes. Risperidone at a low starting dose (0.5–1 mg daily, titrating slowly) is a well-supported first-line choice in first-episode psychosis. Long-acting injectables (option B) are not indicated as first-line in a first episode before oral compliance has been established. Clozapine (option E) is reserved for treatment-resistant schizophrenia after failure of at least two antipsychotics.",
