    correctAnswer: "A",
    explanation: `Once concerns are raised regarding child abuse in general or child sexual abuse, whether through observations in a clinical setting, disclosure by the victim, or any other means that form a reasonable belief in child abuse, the next best step is always immediately child protection services or the police. Informing the police is the best option if there is an imminent risk. No consent is required in cases of children (minors), and their objection to mandatory reporting does not change the obligation whatsoever. In this case, informing the police is the most appropriate option because informing the child protection services is conditioned to Will's consent, which is not necessary.`,
    reference: "amc",
