    explanation: `In children younger than 12 years, the presence of a non-bloody pus-like vaginal discharge is a strong indicator of possible Neisseria gonorrhoeae infection in cases of suspected sexual abuse. Painful vaginal examination (option A), excoriation marks around the genitalia (option B), and a hymen wider than usual (option C) are potential findings in children with sexual abuse, but none is a strong indicator of gonorrhea infection. Disclosure of sexual abuse by the child (option E) is a direct indicator of sexual abuse, but from a clinical standpoint, it is not indicative of gonorrheal infection. Chlamydia and gonorrhea infections in children should always raise suspicion against sexual abuse.`,
