    id: "ethics-amedex-0067",
    topic: "Ethics & Professionalism",
    subtopic: "Consent in Involuntary Mental Health Patients",
    stem: `A 25-year-old man is involuntarily admitted to the mental health ward for treatment of psychosis. On physical examination, he is found to have a 5x5 cm ulcer on the plantar surface of his left foot, requiring wound debridement, irrigation, and intravenous antibiotics. Which one of the following is the most appropriate approach regarding consent for the treatment of his wound?`,
    options: [
      { label: "A", text: `No consent is required as the patient is already involuntarily admitted.` },
      { label: "B", text: `Take consent from the treating psychiatrist.` },
      { label: "C", text: `Take consent from the patient.` },
      { label: "D", text: `Contact the patient's family for informed consent.` },
      { label: "E", text: `Apply to the mental health tribunal for consent for wound debridement.` },
    ],
    correctAnswer: "C",
    explanation: `Patients who are subject to involuntary treatment under the mental health act may still have the capacity to give or decline consent for a specific healthcare matter not related to their current mental illness (for example the use of antibiotics for a chest infection, or a surgical procedure on the limb). Assessment of the patient's capacity to make decisions about every other treatment other than that for the initial problem should be performed in the standard way and documented appropriately. If a patient lacks the capacity to give consent to health care for a condition unrelated to the current mental illness, consent should be sought from a substitute decision-maker in the same order as for other patients who are not legally able to give informed consent. The involuntary treatment order only applies to the current mental health issue and does not cover other areas of treatment.`,
    reference: "amc",
    difficulty: "medium",
